# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 1840-democratic-national-convention
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1821-united-states-senate-election-in-new-york] The **1821 United States Senate election in New York** was held on February 6, 1821, by the New York State Legislature to elect a U.S. senator (Class 1) to represent the State of New York in the United States Senate.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1821-united-states-senate-election-in-new-york] Nathan Sanford had been elected in 1815 to this seat, and his term would expire on March 3, 1821.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1821-united-states-senate-election-in-new-york] Although nominally in the same party, the Democratic-Republicans were split into two fiercely opposing factions: the "Clintonians" (allies of Governor DeWitt Clinton), and "Bucktails" (a combine of the Tammany members from New York City and Clinton's upstate adversaries led by Martin Van Buren).
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1821-united-states-senate-election-in-new-york] The Federalist Party had disbanded, the larger part joining the Clintonians, the others the Bucktails.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1821-united-states-senate-election-in-new-york] At the State election in April 1820, although Clinton was re-elected Governor, a Bucktails majority was elected to the assembly, and five of the eight state senators up for renewal were Bucktails.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1821-united-states-senate-election-in-new-york] The 44th New York State Legislature met from November 7 to 20, 1820; and from January 9 to April 3, 1821, at Albany, New York.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1821-united-states-senate-election-in-new-york] The party strength in the assembly as shown by the vote for Speaker was: 69 for Bucktail Peter Sharpe and 52 for Clintonian John C.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1821-united-states-senate-election-in-new-york] Before the election, a caucus of Democratic-Republican State legislators was held with 82 members present.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1821-united-states-senate-election-in-new-york] 58 voted for Van Buren, 24 for Sanford, and Martin Van Buren was declared nominated.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1821-united-states-senate-election-in-new-york] In the election, he received the votes of the Bucktails.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1821-united-states-senate-election-in-new-york] Disregarding the caucus nominee, a practice now already established, the incumbent U.S.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1821-united-states-senate-election-in-new-york] Senator Nathan Sanford received the votes of the Clintonians.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1821-united-states-senate-election-in-new-york] Martin Van Buren was the choice of both the Assembly and the Senate, and was declared elected.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1828-new-york-gubernatorial-election] The **1828 New York gubernatorial election** was held from November 3 to 5, 1828.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1828-new-york-gubernatorial-election] Incumbent Governor DeWitt Clinton died in office on February 11, 1828.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1828-new-york-gubernatorial-election] Lieutenant Governor Nathaniel Pitcher succeeded him but was not a candidate for election to the next term.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1828-new-york-gubernatorial-election] United States Senator Martin Van Buren was elected Governor over United States Supreme Court Justice Smith Thompson and journalist Solomon Southwick.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1828-new-york-gubernatorial-election] This is the first election to feature a winning candidate who eventually became President of the United States.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1828-new-york-gubernatorial-election] This is the first election to also feature a winning candidate who eventually became both Vice President of the United States and President of the United States.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1828-new-york-gubernatorial-election] The Democratic Party nominated U.S. senator Martin Van Buren.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1828-new-york-gubernatorial-election] They nominated former U.S. representative and Judge of the Seventh Circuit Enos T.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1828-new-york-gubernatorial-election] The National Republican Party nominated Supreme Court Justice Smith Thompson.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1828-new-york-gubernatorial-election] They nominated state assemblyman Francis Granger for Lieutenant Governor.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1828-new-york-gubernatorial-election] The Anti-Masonic Party nominated newspaper publisher Solomon Southwick.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1828-new-york-gubernatorial-election] They nominated state senator John Crary for Lieutenant Governor.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1828-new-york-gubernatorial-election] Van Buren was sworn into office as governor on January 1, 1829, but quickly resigned from office on March 12, 1829, to serve as United States Secretary of State and was succeeded by Lieutenant Governor Enos T.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] Presidential elections were held in the United States from October 31 to December 2, 1828.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] Just as in the 1824 election, President John Quincy Adams of the National Republican Party faced Andrew Jackson of the Democratic Party, making the election the second rematch in presidential history.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] Both parties were new organizations, and this was the first presidential election their nominees contested.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] With the collapse of the Federalist Party, four members of the Democratic-Republican Party, including Jackson and Adams, had sought the presidency in the 1824 election.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] Jackson had won a plurality (but not majority) of both the electoral vote and popular vote in the 1824 election, but had lost the contingent election that was held in the House of Representatives.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] In the aftermath of the election, Jackson's supporters accused Adams and Henry Clay of having reached a "corrupt bargain" in which Clay helped Adams win the contingent election in return for the position of Secretary of State.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] After the 1824 election, Jackson's supporters immediately began plans for a campaign in 1828, and the Democratic-Republican Party fractured into the National Republican Party and the Democratic Party during Adams's presidency.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] The 1828 campaign was marked by large amounts of "mudslinging", as both parties attacked the personal qualities of the opposing party's candidate.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] Jackson dominated in the South and the West, aided in part by the passage of the Tariff of 1828.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] With the ongoing expansion of the right to vote to most white men, the election marked a dramatic expansion of the electorate, with 9.5% of Americans casting a vote for president, compared with 3.4% in 1824.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] Several states transitioned to a popular vote for president, leaving South Carolina and Delaware as the only states in which the legislature chose presidential electors.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] Jackson decisively won the election, carrying 55.5% of the popular vote and 178 electoral votes, to Adams' 83.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] The election marked the rise of Jacksonian Democracy and the transition from the First Party System to the Second Party System.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] Historians debate the significance of the election, with many arguing that it marked the beginning of modern American politics by removing key barriers to voter participation and establishing a stable two-party system.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] Jackson became the first president whose home state was neither Massachusetts nor Virginia, while Adams was the second to lose re-election, following his father John Adams.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] Henry Clay, unsuccessful candidate and Speaker of the House at the time, despised Jackson, in part due to their fight for Western votes during the election, and he chose to support Adams, which led to Adams being elected president on the first ballot.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] A few days after the election, Adams appointed Clay his Secretary of State, a position held by Adams and his three immediate predecessors prior to becoming president.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] Jackson and his followers promptly accused Clay and Adams of striking a "corrupt bargain," and continued to lambaste the president until the 1828 election.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] In 1824, the national Democratic-Republican Party collapsed as national politics became increasingly polarized between supporters of Adams and supporters of Jackson.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] In a prelude to the presidential election, the Jacksonians bolstered their numbers in Congress in the 1826 congressional elections, with Jackson ally Andrew Stevenson chosen as the new Speaker of the House of Representatives in 1827 over Adams ally Speaker, John W.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] In October 1825, the Tennessee legislature re-nominated Jackson for president.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] Congressional opponents of Adams, including former William H.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] Crawford supporter Martin Van Buren, rallied around Jackson's candidacy.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] Jackson's supporters called themselves *Democrats*, and would formally organize as the Democratic Party shortly after his election.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] In hopes of uniting those opposed to Adams, Jackson ran on a ticket with Calhoun.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] No congressional nominating caucus or national convention was held.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] Adams' relationship with Vice President John C.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] Calhoun deteriorated, with Calhoun opposing Clay's appointment as Secretary of State due to his own presidential ambitions.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] In June 1826, Calhoun gave his support to Jackson for the 1828 election.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] Calhoun's stance on the removal of Native Americans was not accepted by the Georgian electors who instead voted for William Smith.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] Van Buren, who supported Crawford during the 1824 election, supported Jackson during the 1828 election and aided in the selection of Calhoun as vice president in order to prevent DeWitt Clinton, his political enemy, from being selected.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] Van Buren arranged for incidents to divide Calhoun and Adams such as him abstaining from a vote on tariff legislation supported by Adams in order for Calhoun to break the tie by voting against it.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] Thomas Ritchie, editor of the *Richmond Examiner*, was one of the leading supporters of Crawford during the 1824 election and Van Buren convinced him to support Jackson.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] Van Buren convinced him of an alliance "between the planters of the South and the plain Republicans of the North".
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] Adams was re-nominated on the endorsement of state legislatures and partisan rallies.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] As with the Democrats, no nominating caucus or national convention was held.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] Adams chose Secretary of the Treasury Richard Rush, a Pennsylvanian known for his protectionist views, as his running mate.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] Adams, who was personally popular in New England, hoped to assemble a coalition in which Clay attracted Western voters, Rush attracted voters in the middle states, and Webster won over former members of the Federalist Party.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] Adams support in New York aligned with the Anti-Masonic Party and Thurlow Weed, his campaign manager in the state, was sympathetic to the anti-masonic movement.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] The campaign was marked by large amounts of nasty "mudslinging." Jackson's marriage, for example, came in for the vicious attack.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] Charles Hammond, in his *Cincinnati Gazette*, asked: "Ought a convicted adulteress and her paramour husband be placed in the highest offices of this free and Christian land?" At the time of the election, Mr. and Mrs.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] Jackson had been happily, legally married for almost 35 years, but when they met, Rachel had been legally married to Lewis Robards.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] In the Adams campaign managers' hands, this became a scandal.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] Decades later, their youthful love story became a political liability.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] Jackson believed that attacks on him were personal vendettas consequent to past disputes, writing, "I am branded with every crime, and Doctor McNary, Col.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] Erwin, Anderson and Williams are associated for this purpose." One thing that all these men had in common is that they had all known and/or been business partners and/or been military comrades of Jackson going back decades.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] Jackson's campaigners fired back by claiming that while serving as minister to Russia, Adams had procured a young girl to serve as a prostitute for Emperor Alexander I.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] They also stated that Adams had a billiard table in the White House and that he had charged the government for it.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] (In fact Adams while minister to Russia had employed a young girl as a maid to his wife; the girl had written a letter which had been intercepted by the Russian postal services.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] Alexander I had been curious to meet the letter writer publicly at court and Adams had done so.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] The billiard table was Adams' personal property; a bill for repairing it had been accidentally included in the White House expense accounts.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] Adams also came under attack for having a chess set).
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] Jackson also came under heavy attack as a slave trader who bought and sold slaves and moved them about in defiance of modern standards of morality (he was not attacked for merely owning slaves used in plantation work).
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] The Coffin Handbills attacked Jackson for his courts-martial, execution of deserters, and massacres of Indian villages, and also his habit of dueling and that he supposedly fought over 100 duels.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] In fact, Jackson had only fought three duels: in the first both men had fired at each other but made up; in the second duel, Jackson vs John Sevier, it had taken place but only two persons not connected with either party had been slightly injured.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] The third duel was with Charles Dickinson in which Dickinson was mortally wounded while Jackson was left with a bullet in his chest.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] A so-called fourth duel between Jackson and Thomas Hart Benton was in fact a frontier brawl which left Jackson badly wounded in the shoulder.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] That said the list of violent incidents involving Andrew Jackson began with his arrival in Tennessee in the 1780s and continued apace for years.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] Ezra Stiles Ely attacked Adams' Unitarian beliefs and called for Christians to vote for Jackson.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] Jackson avoided articulating issue positions, instead campaigning on his personal qualities and his opposition to Adams.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] Adams avoided popular campaigning, instead emphasizing his support of specific issues.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] Adams's praise of internal improvements in Europe, such as "lighthouses of the skies" (observatories), in his first annual message to Congress, and his suggestion that Congress not be "palsied by the will of our constituents" were given attention in and out of the press.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] People kissed babies, had picnics, and started many other traditions during the campaign.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] Jefferson wrote of the outcome of the contingent election of 1825 in a letter to William H.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] In the next election, Jackson's and Adams's supporters saw value in establishing the opinion of Jefferson in regards to their respective candidates and against their opposition.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] Jefferson died on July 4, 1826, on the same day as his predecessor, John Adams, Adams's father.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] Webster recorded that Jefferson told him in December 1824 that Jackson was a dangerous man unfit for the presidency.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] Historian Sean Wilentz described Webster's account of the meeting as "not wholly reliable." Biographer Robert V.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] Gilmer accused Coles of misrepresentation, in Jefferson's opinion had changed, Gilmer said.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] Jefferson's son-in-law, former Virginia Governor Thomas Mann Randolph Jr., said in 1826 that Jefferson had a "strong repugnance" to Henry Clay.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] Others said the same thing, but Coles could not believe Jefferson's opinion had changed.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] Giles released a letter from Jefferson meant to be kept private to Thomas Ritchie's *Richmond Enquirer*.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] It was written after Adams's first annual message to Congress and it contained an attack from Jefferson on the incumbent administration.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] Giles omitted a prior letter of Jefferson's praise of Adams for his role in the embargo of 1808.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] Thomas Jefferson Randolph soon collected and published Jefferson's correspondence.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] 22.2% of the voting age population and 57.3% of eligible voters participated in the election.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] All of the states, except for Delaware and South Carolina, selected their electors through a popular vote.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] The selection of electors began on October 31 with elections in Ohio and Pennsylvania and ended on November 13 with elections in North Carolina.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] The Electoral College met on December 3.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] Adams won the same states that his father had won in the election of 1800 (the New England states, New Jersey, and Delaware) and Maryland, but Jackson won all other states and won the election in a landslide.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] The Democratic Party in Georgia was hopelessly divided into two factions (Troup and Clark) at the time.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] Despite this, both factions nominated Jackson for President, with the election being primarily a test of the strength of these two factions - the Adams electors ran a very poor third, with just 3.21% of the vote.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] The winning slate, which received a 3,000 vote majority.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] Jackson received 50.3% of the vote in states without slavery while he received 72.6% of the vote in states with slavery.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] He received 200,000 votes in the South and 400,000 votes in the North, but the Three-fifths Compromise, which inflated the South's electoral votes, resulted in him receiving 105 electoral votes from the South and 73 votes from the North.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] This was the first election in American history in which the incumbent president lost re-election despite winning a greater share of the popular vote than in the previous election.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] Adams' loss was also the second time an elected president lost the popular vote twice, this also occurred with Benjamin Harrison in 1888 and 1892, and Donald Trump who lost the popular vote in 2016 and 2020.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] This was the last election in which the Democrats won Kentucky until 1856.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] It is also the only election where Maine, New Hampshire, New Jersey, and Vermont voted for the National Republicans, and the last time that New Hampshire voted against the Democrats until 1856.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] It was also the only election in which an electoral vote split occurred in Maine until the election of 2016, the first election in which the winning ticket did not have a north–south balance, and the first election in which two northerners ran against two southerners.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] (b) *Votes cast for Jackson electors nominated by the Clark faction of the Democratic Party of Georgia.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] Two tickets pledged to Jackson ran in this state; the Clark ticket was defeated by electors nominated by the Troup faction.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] There were two Jackson tickets in Georgia representing different factions of the party.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] The Troup faction "won" with 9,712 votes and the Clarke faction lost with 7,991.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] They are combined here, though legally this is incorrect.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] The state rejected returns from 10 counties and 8 others submitted none.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] Including the rejected returns, the total votes are Jackson (Troup) 10,508, Jackson (Clarke) 8,854 and Adams, 642.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] In Maryland's 3rd and 4th districts, voters voted for two electors, with each pledged to one candidate or another.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] The votes in the 3rd were 6,177 for William Fitzhugh Jr. and 6,164 for William Tyler, both for Jackson, versus 6,117 for George Baltzell and William Price for Adams.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] In the 4th the votes were 6,058 for Benjamin Chew Howard and James Sewell for Jackson versus 5,743 and 5,742 for the Adams electors.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] Note: Dubin mistakenly swapped the 3rd and 4th districts in his book, but that has been corrected here.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] Two statewide electors were chosen by the electors elected at the district level.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] Rachel Jackson had been having chest pains throughout the campaign, and she was traumatized by the personal attacks on her marriage.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] She became ill and died on December 22, 1828.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] Jackson accused the Adams campaign, and Henry Clay even more so, of causing her death, saying, "I can and do forgive all my enemies.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] Andrew Jackson was sworn in as president on March 4, 1829.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] After the inauguration, a mob entered the White House to shake the new president's hand, damaging the furniture and lights.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] Jackson escaped through the back, and large punch bowls were set up to lure the crowd outside.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] Conservatives were horrified at this event, and held it up as a portent of terrible things to come from the first Democratic president.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] When Jackson arrived in Washington, D.C., he was to pay the customary courtesy call on the outgoing president, but he refused to do so.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] John Quincy Adams responded by refusing to go to the inauguration of Andrew Jackson, similar to his father who did not attend the inauguration of Thomas Jefferson 28 years before.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1831-national-republican-national-convention] The **1831 National Republican National Convention** was held to determine the presidential ticket of the National Republican Party in the 1832 United States presidential election.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1831-national-republican-national-convention] The convention was held in Baltimore, Maryland in December 1831.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1831-national-republican-national-convention] The party nominated Senator Henry Clay of Kentucky for president and former Representative John Sergeant of Pennsylvania for vice president.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1831-national-republican-national-convention] The 1831 National Republican National Convention was the first U.S. presidential nominating convention held by a major party, though a third party, the Anti-Masonic Party, had held a presidential nominating convention earlier in 1831.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1831-national-republican-national-convention] 155 delegates from 18 of the 24 states attended the convention.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1831-national-republican-national-convention] Clay was the unanimous choice for president of the party's delegates.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1831-national-republican-national-convention] He was the first sitting member of the United States Senate to be nominated for president.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1831-national-republican-national-convention] In the 1832 presidential election, Clay was defeated by President Andrew Jackson of the Democratic Party.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1831-national-republican-national-convention] After the 1832 election, the National Republican Party, the Anti-Masonic Party, and other opponents of Jackson coalesced into the Whig Party.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1831-national-republican-national-convention] Thus, the 1831 convention was the only national convention ever held by the National Republican Party.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1832-democratic-national-convention] The **1832 Democratic National Convention** was held from May 21 to May 23, 1832, in Baltimore, Maryland.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1832-democratic-national-convention] In the first presidential nominating convention ever held by the Democratic Party, incumbent President Andrew Jackson was nominated for a second term, while former Secretary of State Martin Van Buren was nominated for vice president.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1832-democratic-national-convention] The Anti-Masonic Party and the National Republican Party had held the first presidential nominating conventions in 1831, and Jackson's "Kitchen Cabinet" helped organize a Democratic convention in 1832.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1832-democratic-national-convention] As the party leaders assumed that Jackson would be nominated for president, the primary purpose of the convention was to find a new running mate: Vice President John C.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1832-democratic-national-convention] Calhoun had fallen out with Jackson following the Petticoat affair and the Nullification Crisis, and subsequently resigned the office in order to take a Senate seat.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1832-democratic-national-convention] The convention, which was presided over by Governor Robert Lucas, hosted delegates from every state except Missouri; Jackson won the presidential nomination unanimously.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1832-democratic-national-convention] With Jackson's strong endorsement, Van Buren easily won the vice presidential nomination on the first ballot, defeating former Representative Philip P.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1832-democratic-national-convention] Barbour of Virginia and Representative Richard Mentor Johnson of Kentucky.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1832-democratic-national-convention] The Democratic ticket of Jackson and Van Buren went on to win the 1832 presidential election.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1832-democratic-national-convention] In the summer of 1822, "Richmond Junto" leader Thomas Ritchie of Virginia began raising the idea of a national convention to resolve the issue of nomination; ultimately, the congressional nominating caucus was appealed to by the devotees of Treasury Secretary William H.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1832-democratic-national-convention] Following that defeat in the election of 1824, early in 1827, Van Buren privately made the argument to Richie for an exclusive national convention of Republicans to ensure Jackson's nomination.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1832-democratic-national-convention] However, it did not immediately come to fruition while state conventions and legislatures took up Jackson as their presidential candidate for the election of 1828 with Vice President John C.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1832-democratic-national-convention] Such a type of national convention would occur after the election.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1832-democratic-national-convention] Calhoun soon became politically estranged from President Jackson, due in part to an 1830 letter written by Crawford stating that Calhoun, as Secretary of War under President James Monroe, pushed for a reprimand of then-General Jackson for his actions in the 1818 invasion of Florida.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1832-democratic-national-convention] The Petticoat affair in which Calhoun's wife, Floride, was a central figure further alienated Jackson from the vice president and his supporters.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1832-democratic-national-convention] The final blow to the relationship came in January 1832, when Calhoun, as President of the Senate, sank Van Buren's nomination as Minister to Great Britain by casting a tie-breaking vote in the United States Senate.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1832-democratic-national-convention] Consequently, Calhoun was replaced as the party's 1832 vice presidential nominee by Van Buren.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1832-democratic-national-convention] Later that year, on December 28, he resigned as vice president, after having been elected to the U.S.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1832-democratic-national-convention] There he continued to be a proponent of the doctrine of nullification in opposition to Jackson.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1832-democratic-national-convention] The proposal for the convention began with members of Jackson's "Kitchen Cabinet", his coterie of informal advisers and confidants.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1832-democratic-national-convention] Major William Berkeley Lewis wrote on May 25, 1831, to Amos Kendall, who was then in New Hampshire.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1832-democratic-national-convention] He proposed that the New Hampshire legislature call for a national gathering of Republican supporters of the Jackson administration to nominate a candidate for the vice presidency, and asked Kendall to pass the idea to Isaac Hill.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1832-democratic-national-convention] The convention was called to order by Frederick A.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1832-democratic-national-convention] Delegates from all states except Missouri were present.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1832-democratic-national-convention] Governor Robert Lucas of Ohio served as the chairman and convention president.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1832-democratic-national-convention] Peter Vivian Daniel, James Fenner, John M.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1832-democratic-national-convention] Barclay, and Augustin Smith Clayton were chosen as convention vice presidents.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1832-democratic-national-convention] John Adams Dix was appointed secretary at the first meeting, with other additional secretaries thereafter.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1832-democratic-national-convention] A resolution was passed by the convention requiring two-thirds majority support of the delegates for a nomination.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1832-democratic-national-convention] An address by the Republican delegates of New York gave a history of previous national political activity in the United States.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1832-democratic-national-convention] They denounced the National Republicans as Federalists under a new designation and they denounced the Nullifiers while they declared that their own party held the middle ground between the positions of the other two.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1832-democratic-national-convention] The address described what they claimed were political similarities between Andrew Jackson and Thomas Jefferson and it defended the policies of Jackson's administration.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1832-democratic-national-convention] It characterized Van Buren as a strict constructionist and welcomed his nomination.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1832-democratic-national-convention] The convention concluded by adopting a resolution calling for an address or report from the delegations to their constituents.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1832-democratic-national-convention] Jackson was nominated via a resolution passed by the convention, affirming the nominations which Jackson had previously received from multiple state legislatures.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1832-democratic-national-convention] Martin Van Buren was nominated for vice president on the first ballot after receiving 208 votes of the 283 cast, 19 more than the two-thirds majority required to win.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1832-democratic-national-convention] Andrew Jackson and Martin Van Buren defeated their main competitors, Henry Clay and John Sergeant of the National Republican Party, by a large electoral vote margin in the election of 1832.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1832-united-states-presidential-election] Presidential elections were held in the United States from November 2 to December 5, 1832.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1832-united-states-presidential-election] Incumbent president Andrew Jackson, candidate of the Democratic Party, defeated Henry Clay, candidate of the National Republican Party.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1832-united-states-presidential-election] The election saw the first use of the presidential nominating conventions, and the Democrats, National Republicans, and the Anti-Masonic Party all used conventions to select their candidates.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1832-united-states-presidential-election] Jackson won renomination with no opposition, and the 1832 Democratic National Convention replaced Vice President John C.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1832-united-states-presidential-election] The National Republican Convention nominated a ticket led by Clay, a Kentuckian who had served as Secretary of State under President John Quincy Adams.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1832-united-states-presidential-election] The Anti-Masonic Party, one of the first major U.S. third parties, nominated former Attorney General William Wirt.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1832-united-states-presidential-election] Jackson faced heavy criticism for his actions in the Bank War, but remained popular among the general public.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1832-united-states-presidential-election] He won a majority of the popular vote and 219 of the 288 electoral votes, carrying most states outside New England.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1832-united-states-presidential-election] Clay won 37.4% of the popular vote and 49 electoral votes, while Wirt won 7.8% of the popular vote and carried the state of Vermont.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1832-united-states-presidential-election] After the election, members of the National Republican Party and the Anti-Masonic Party formed the Whig Party, which became the Democrats' primary opponent over the next two decades.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1832-united-states-presidential-election] With the demise of the congressional nominating caucus in the election of 1824, the political system was left without an institutional method on the national level for determining presidential nominations.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1832-united-states-presidential-election] For this reason, the candidates of 1832 were chosen by national conventions.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1832-united-states-presidential-election] The first national convention was held by the Anti-Masonic Party in Baltimore, Maryland, in September 1831.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1832-united-states-presidential-election] The National Republican Party and the Democratic Party soon imitated them, also holding conventions in Baltimore, which would remain a favored venue for national political conventions for decades.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1832-united-states-presidential-election] President Jackson and Vice President Calhoun had a strained relationship for a number of reasons, most notably a difference in opinion about the Nullification Crisis and the involvement of Calhoun's wife Floride in the Eaton affair.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1832-united-states-presidential-election] As a result, Secretary of State Martin Van Buren and Secretary of War John H.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1832-united-states-presidential-election] Eaton resigned from office in April 1831, and Jackson requested the resignation of all other cabinet officers except one.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1832-united-states-presidential-election] Van Buren instigated the procedure as a means of removing Calhoun supporters from the Cabinet.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1832-united-states-presidential-election] Calhoun further aggravated Jackson in the summer of 1831 when he issued his "Fort Hill Letter," in which he outlined the constitutional basis for a state's ability to nullify an act of Congress.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1832-united-states-presidential-election] The final blow to the Jackson-Calhoun relationship came when Jackson nominated Van Buren to serve as Minister to Great Britain and the vote in the Senate ended in a tie, which Calhoun broke by voting against confirmation on January 25, 1832.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1832-united-states-presidential-election] In January it was not clear who the Democrats' candidates would be in the election later that year.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1832-united-states-presidential-election] Jackson had already been nominated by several state legislatures, following the pattern in 1824 and 1828, but he worried that the various state parties would not unite on a vice-presidential nominee.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1832-united-states-presidential-election] As a result, the Democratic Party followed the pattern of the opposition and called a national convention.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1832-united-states-presidential-election] The 1832 Democratic National Convention, the Democratic Party's first, was held in the Athenaeum in Baltimore (the same venue as the two opposition parties) from May 21 to May 23, 1832.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1832-united-states-presidential-election] Several decisions were made at the convention.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1832-united-states-presidential-election] On the first day, a committee was appointed to provide a list of delegates from each state.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1832-united-states-presidential-election] This committee, later called the Credentials Committee, reported that all states were represented.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1832-united-states-presidential-election] Delegates were present from the District of Columbia, and on the first contested roll call vote in convention history, the convention voted 126–153 to deprive the District of Columbia of its voting rights in the convention.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1832-united-states-presidential-election] The Rules Committee gave a brief report that established several other customs.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1832-united-states-presidential-election] Each state was allotted as many votes as it had presidential electors; several states were overrepresented and many were underrepresented.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1832-united-states-presidential-election] Second, balloting was taken by states and not by individual delegates.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1832-united-states-presidential-election] Third, two-thirds of the delegates would have to support a candidate for nomination, a measure intended to reduce sectional strife.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1832-united-states-presidential-election] The fourth rule, which banned nomination speeches, was the only one the party quickly abandoned.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1832-united-states-presidential-election] No roll call vote was taken to nominate Jackson for a second term.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1832-united-states-presidential-election] Instead, the convention passed a resolution stating that "we most cordially concur in the repeated nominations which he has received in various parts of the union." Martin Van Buren was nominated for vice president on the first ballot, receiving 208 votes to 49 for Philip P.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1832-united-states-presidential-election] Barbour and 26 for Richard Mentor Johnson.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1832-united-states-presidential-election] Afterward, the convention approved an address to the nation and adjourned.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1832-united-states-presidential-election] Virginia Democrats opposed to Van Buren's candidacy held a convention in June 1832 in Staunton, Virginia.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1832-united-states-presidential-election] Jackson was nominated for president and Philip P.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1832-united-states-presidential-election] Barbour withdrew, but the ticket appeared on the ballot in Alabama, Georgia, Mississippi, North Carolina, and Virginia.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1832-united-states-presidential-election] Barbour's supporters in Alabama, North Carolina, and South Carolina also organized tickets.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1832-united-states-presidential-election] Soon after the Anti-Masonic Party held its national convention, supporters of Henry Clay called a national convention of the National Republican Party.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1832-united-states-presidential-election] 18 of the 24 states sent delegations to the convention, which convened on December 12, 1831.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1832-united-states-presidential-election] The convention was attended by 168 delegates from eighteen states although one-fourth of the delegates were late due to winter weather.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1832-united-states-presidential-election] On the convention's fourth day, the roll call ballot for president took place.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1832-united-states-presidential-election] The chairman of the convention called the name of each delegate, who gave his vote orally.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1832-united-states-presidential-election] Clay received 155 votes, with delegate Frederick H.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1832-united-states-presidential-election] Shuman of North Carolina abstaining because he believed that Clay could not win and should wait until 1836.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1832-united-states-presidential-election] As additional delegates arrived, they were allowed to cast their votes for Clay, and by the end of the convention he had 167 votes to one abstention.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1832-united-states-presidential-election] A similar procedure was used for the vice-presidential ballot.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1832-united-states-presidential-election] Former Congressman John Sergeant of Pennsylvania was nominated with 64 votes to six abstentions.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1832-united-states-presidential-election] A prominent Philadelphia attorney with connections to the Second Bank of the United States and a reputation as an opponent of slavery, Sergeant gave the ticket geographical balance.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1832-united-states-presidential-election] The first national nominating convention for a presidential candidate in American history was held by the Anti-Masonic Party in Baltimore, Maryland from September 26–28, 1831.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1832-united-states-presidential-election] The convention was attended by 116 delegates from thirteen states with Maryland being the furthest state in the South represented.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1832-united-states-presidential-election] The leaders of the party attempted to give the presidential nomination to Clay and Supreme Court Justice John McLean, but both declined.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1832-united-states-presidential-election] Several prominent politicians were considered for the presidential nomination.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1832-united-states-presidential-election] Richard Rush would have been the nominee, but pointedly refused.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1832-united-states-presidential-election] As a result of this action, along with his softness toward Jackson, former President John Quincy Adams never forgave him.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1832-united-states-presidential-election] Adams was willing to run as the Anti-Masonic candidate, but the party leaders did not want to risk running someone so unpopular.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1832-united-states-presidential-election] The delegates met behind closed doors for several days before the convention officially opened, making some initial decisions.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1832-united-states-presidential-election] Several unofficial presidential ballots and one official ballot were taken, in which William Wirt defeated Rush and John McLean for the nomination.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1832-united-states-presidential-election] Ironically, Wirt was a Mason and even defended the Order in a speech before the convention that nominated him.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1832-united-states-presidential-election] Wirt hoped for an endorsement from the National Republicans.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1832-united-states-presidential-election] When the National Republican Party nominated Henry Clay, Wirt's position became awkward.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1832-united-states-presidential-election] He did not withdraw, even though he had no chance of being elected.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1832-united-states-presidential-election] The convention was organized on September 26 and heard reports of its committees on the 27th.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1832-united-states-presidential-election] The 28th was spent on the official roll call for president and vice president.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1832-united-states-presidential-election] During the balloting, each delegate's name was called, after which that delegate placed a written ballot in a special box.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1832-united-states-presidential-election] Wirt was nominated for president with 108 votes to one for Rush and two abstentions.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1832-united-states-presidential-election] Amos Ellmaker was nominated for vice president with 108 votes to one for John C.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1832-united-states-presidential-election] Spencer (chairman of the convention) and two abstentions.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1832-united-states-presidential-election] While the South Carolina state legislature remained nominally under Democratic control, it refused to support Jackson's reelection due to the ongoing Nullification Crisis, and instead opted to back a ticket proposed by the Nullifier Party led by John C.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1832-united-states-presidential-election] The Nullifiers were made up of former members of the Democratic-Republican Party who had largely supported Jackson at the previous election, but were much stauncher proponents of states' rights, which ultimately led them to repudiate Jackson during his first term.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1832-united-states-presidential-election] Calhoun himself declined to head the ticket, instead nominating Governor of Virginia John Floyd, who also opposed Jackson's stance on states' rights.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1832-united-states-presidential-election] Merchant and economist Henry Lee was nominated as Floyd's running mate.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1832-united-states-presidential-election] Ultimately, Floyd's candidacy amounted to little more than a protest against Jackson, as his ticket did not run in any state outside of South Carolina.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1832-united-states-presidential-election] He nonetheless received all the state's electoral votes.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1832-united-states-presidential-election] Jackson rode into office in 1828 on the strength of a coalition that included southern opponents of the Tariff of 1828, western advocates of internal improvements, many former Democratic-Republicans, and some former Federalists.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1832-united-states-presidential-election] Henry Clay predicted this unwieldy marriage of disparate and in many cases hostile interests would soon collapse under the pressures of office.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1832-united-states-presidential-election] Clay determined to split the Jacksonian party on the issue of the American System by engineering a confrontation over the Second Bank of the United States.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1832-united-states-presidential-election] He persuaded the president of the bank, Nicholas Biddle, to request recharter a full four years early in order to coincide with the presidential election.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1832-united-states-presidential-election] As expected, Jackson vetoed the recharter bill and issued a stinging veto message criticizing the bank's interference in national politics.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1832-united-states-presidential-election] Clay predicted the president's hostility to the nationalist economic program would prove unpopular with voters, particularly in Pennsylvania where the bank was headquartered, and hand the Anti-Jacksonians victory at the polls.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1832-united-states-presidential-election] Simultaneously, Jackson faced defections from the southern wing of his party over the Nullification Crisis.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1832-united-states-presidential-election] These southerners objected strongly to the tariff and argued for the right of the states to nullify unfriendly federal laws, a position Jackson refused to endorse.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1832-united-states-presidential-election] Clay hoped to bring the disgruntled ex-Jacksonians into the fold, but his tactic of promoting the American System as the major issue of the campaign was ill-designed for this purpose.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1832-united-states-presidential-election] While some Southerners did favor the bank, they were unwilling to break publicly with Jackson on this issue, and Vice President Calhoun was overtly hostile to the American System by 1832.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1832-united-states-presidential-election] In South Carolina, the faction loyal to Calhoun nominated a slate of independent electors who voted for Governor John Floyd of Virginia.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1832-united-states-presidential-election] Elsewhere, dissident Southern Jacksonians protested the nomination of Martin Van Buren by supporting Philip P.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1832-united-states-presidential-election] Barbour for vice president but were unwilling to break with Jackson himself.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1832-united-states-presidential-election] As the Barbour movement suggests, Jackson's personal popularity worked against the growth of opposition politics in the South despite the growing dissatisfaction with the national administration.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1832-united-states-presidential-election] Meanwhile, Jackson's northern opponents were hurt by the divided state of the opposition.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1832-united-states-presidential-election] The failure of Anti-Jacksonians to unite behind a single candidate for president alarmed leaders like William Henry Seward and Thurlow Weed, who worked feverishly to avoid a disastrous split in the opposition vote.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1832-united-states-presidential-election] In New York, Ohio, and Pennsylvania, Anti-Masons and National Republicans organized fusion tickets with electors pledged to support whichever candidate stood the best chance of defeating Jackson in the electoral college.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1832-united-states-presidential-election] Jackson carried all three states, however, along with their combined 93 electoral votes.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1832-united-states-presidential-election] His margin in Pennsylvania was much reduced from 1828, but still wider than the Democratic majority in the gubernatorial election held in October, due largely to the drop in support for the Anti-Masons.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1832-united-states-presidential-election] The Anti-Jacksonian "Union ticket" foreshadowed the merger of both parties with disaffected Southern Jacksonians in 1834 to form the Whig Party, which would constitute the major opposition to the Jacksonian Democrats for the remainder of the Second Party System.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1832-united-states-presidential-election] While Clay hoped to alienate the different wings of the Democratic Party from each other by promoting the bank as an issue, his strategy backfired, as Jackson's veto message compellingly portrayed him as the defender of the common people against the furious assault of the financial interests.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1832-united-states-presidential-election] Events of the previous decade had not endeared the bank to working people, and they identified with Jackson's portrait of the "Monster Bank" as corrupt, self-interested, and destructive to democratic egalitarianism.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1832-united-states-presidential-election] Meanwhile, Clay's high-handed treatment of the Anti-Masons discouraged unity among Anti-Jacksonians, and the unpopularity of the National Republicans frustrated efforts to unite all opponents of the administration under a single roof.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1832-united-states-presidential-election] 20.6% of the voting age population and 56.7% of eligible voters participated in the election.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1832-united-states-presidential-election] Jackson won the election in an electoral college landslide.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1832-united-states-presidential-election] Jackson received 219 electoral votes, defeating Clay (49), Floyd (11), and Wirt (7) by a large margin.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1832-united-states-presidential-election] Jackson's popularity with the American public and the vitality of the political movement with which he was associated is confirmed by the fact that no president was again able to secure a majority of the popular vote in two consecutive elections until Ulysses S.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1832-united-states-presidential-election] Only two other presidents from the Democratic party were ever able to replicate this feat: Franklin D.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1832-united-states-presidential-election] Roosevelt (for the first time in 1936) and Barack Obama (in 2012).
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1832-united-states-presidential-election] Furthermore, no president succeeded in securing re-election again until Abraham Lincoln in 1864, and no Democrat would secure a second consecutive term until Woodrow Wilson in 1916.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1832-united-states-presidential-election] As of 2024, Jackson was the second of eight presidential nominees to win a significant number of electoral votes in at least three elections, the others being Thomas Jefferson, Henry Clay, Grover Cleveland, William Jennings Bryan, Franklin D.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1832-united-states-presidential-election] Roosevelt, Richard Nixon, and Donald Trump.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1832-united-states-presidential-election] Of these, Jackson, Cleveland, and Roosevelt, also won the popular vote in at least three elections.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1832-united-states-presidential-election] Jackson was the second of only five presidents to win re-election with a smaller percentage of the popular vote than in prior elections, the other four are James Madison in 1812, Grover Cleveland in 1892, Franklin D.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1832-united-states-presidential-election] Roosevelt in 1940 and 1944 and Barack Obama in 2012.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1832-united-states-presidential-election] Following the election and Clay's defeat, an Anti-Jackson coalition would be formed out of National Republicans, Anti-Masons, disaffected Jacksonians, and small remnants of the Federalist Party whose last political activity was with them a decade before.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1832-united-states-presidential-election] In the short term, it formed the Whig Party in a coalition against President Jackson and his reforms.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1832-united-states-presidential-election] (a) *The popular vote figures exclude South Carolina where the Electors were chosen by the state legislature rather than by popular vote.* (b) *66,706 Pennsylvanians voted for the Union slate, which represented both Clay and Wirt.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1832-united-states-presidential-election] The 1832 presidential election results are displayed in the maps below.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1835-democratic-national-convention] The **1835 Democratic National Convention** was held from May 20 to May 22, 1835, in Baltimore, Maryland.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1835-democratic-national-convention] The convention nominated incumbent Vice President Martin Van Buren for president and Representative Richard Mentor Johnson of Kentucky for vice president.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1835-democratic-national-convention] Former Speaker of the House Andrew Stevenson served as the convention chairman.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1835-democratic-national-convention] With the support of President Andrew Jackson, Van Buren won the presidential nomination unanimously.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1835-democratic-national-convention] Johnson narrowly won the two-thirds majority necessary for the vice presidential nomination, overcoming a challenge from William Cabell Rives of Virginia.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1835-democratic-national-convention] The Democratic ticket of Van Buren and Johnson went on to win the 1836 presidential election.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1835-democratic-national-convention] On February 23, 1835, President Andrew Jackson wrote to James Gwin of Tennessee and claimed a preference for someone who would "most likely to be the choice of the great body of republicans" in regard to his successor.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1835-democratic-national-convention] He expressed the desire to hold another national convention to nominate candidates for the presidency and vice presidency.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1835-democratic-national-convention] He instructed Gwin to show the letter to the editor of the *Nashville Republican*.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1835-democratic-national-convention] The newspaper later reprinted the letter.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1835-democratic-national-convention] Andrew Stevenson of Virginia served as the chairman and convention president.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1835-democratic-national-convention] Six convention vice presidents and four secretaries were appointed.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1835-democratic-national-convention] Tennessee, Illinois, South Carolina, and Alabama sent no delegates to the convention.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1835-democratic-national-convention] President Jackson had long planned for Vice President Martin Van Buren to succeed him, and Van Buren was the unanimous choice of the delegates for the presidency.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1835-democratic-national-convention] Jackson and other major Democrats had settled on Richard Mentor Johnson, a Kentucky representative who had fought in the War of 1812, as Van Buren's running mate, but many Virginia Democrats backed William Cabell Rives, the former Ambassador to France.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1835-democratic-national-convention] A man from Tennessee, Edward Rucker, who was present at the convention but was not sent as a delegate, cast all 15 votes Tennessee was entitled to for Van Buren, and for Johnson for the vice presidential nomination.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1835-democratic-national-convention] Johnson was nominated for vice president after winning one vote more than the two-thirds majority required.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1835-democratic-national-convention] The delegation of Virginia declared that it had no confidence in Johnson's character and principles, and would not support him.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1835-democratic-national-convention] Letters went out on May 23 from the convention president and vice presidents asking for the acceptance of the nominations by the nominees.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1835-democratic-national-convention] Van Buren replied and accepted the nomination on May 29; Johnson, likewise on June 9.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1835-democratic-national-convention] The Whigs did not put forward a national ticket nominated by national convention.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1835-democratic-national-convention] Van Buren defeated his many competitors for the presidency in the general election.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1835-democratic-national-convention] While the electors of Virginia supported Van Buren for the presidency, they cast their vice presidential votes for William Smith.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1835-democratic-national-convention] Consequently, Johnson received a plurality, but not a majority, of the electoral votes for the vice presidency.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1835-democratic-national-convention] In the subsequent contingent election in the Senate, Johnson was elected vice president.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1840-democratic-national-convention] The **1840 Democratic National Convention** was held in Baltimore, Maryland, from May 5 to May 6.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1840-democratic-national-convention] The Democratic Party re-nominated President Martin Van Buren by acclamation, but failed to select a nominee for vice president.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1840-democratic-national-convention] Van Buren is the only major party presidential nominee since the ratification of the Twelfth Amendment to seek election without a running mate.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1840-democratic-national-convention] Dragged down by the unpopularity of the Panic of 1837, Van Buren was defeated by the Whig Party's ticket in the 1840 presidential election.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1840-democratic-national-convention] Delegates from 21 of 26 states were in attendance.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1840-democratic-national-convention] States not in attendance were Connecticut, Delaware, Illinois, South Carolina and Virginia.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1840-democratic-national-convention] The 1840 convention was the first at which the party adopted a platform.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1840-democratic-national-convention] Delegates reaffirmed their belief that the Constitution was the primary guide for each state's political affairs.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1840-democratic-national-convention] To them, this meant that all roles of the federal government not specifically defined fell to each respective state government, including such responsibilities as debt created by local projects.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1840-democratic-national-convention] Decentralized power and states' rights pervaded each and every resolution adopted at the convention, including those on slavery, taxes, and the possibility of a central bank.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1840-democratic-national-convention] Johnson was not retained on the ticket, as he was largely seen as a liability in the 1836 election and had focused much of his time as vice president on his own economic affairs.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1840-democratic-national-convention] Former president Andrew Jackson backed James K.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1840-democratic-national-convention] Polk for the position of vice president, but Van Buren supported his vice president's renomination.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1840-democratic-national-convention] Prior to the convention, several prominent Democrats sought the vice presidential nomination.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1840-democratic-national-convention] Among them were Polk; Senator William R.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1840-democratic-national-convention] King of Alabama; and Secretary of State John Forsyth of Georgia.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1840-democratic-national-convention] The convention ultimately failed to nominate a running mate for Van Buren.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1840-democratic-national-convention] Van Buren remains the only major party presidential nominee since the passage of the Twelfth Amendment to seek election without a running mate.
[src:1840-democratic-national-convention/1840-democratic-national-convention] Polk and Johnson would both receive electoral votes for vice president in the general election.
